			<title>Guild Wars 2 Sylari Lore Theory</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?74033-Sylari-Lore-Theory&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Tue, 28 Aug 2012 00:53:50 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[I'm stuck at work and won't be able to play today, so thought I would share an interesting theory I saw a few weeks ago concerning the Sylvari. Note that the information I will be discussing can all be gleaned from the first areas of the game, but I am going to put it in spoiler tags anyway because...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>I'm stuck at work and won't be able to play today, so thought I would share an interesting theory I saw a few weeks ago concerning the Sylvari. Note that the information I will be discussing can all be gleaned from the first areas of the game, but I am going to put it in spoiler tags anyway because it has the potential to be a huge deal later on, if proven true.<br />
<br />
I saw the theory while checking to see if WoodenPotatoes had another lore video. He in turn got the information from some forum he reads. I'm going to summarize the information as I understand it, but I'll link the video if you want to listen rather than read. I sort of felt like he took too long getting to the issue.<br />
<br />
So one more warning, don't read this if you care about (possible) spoilers.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px"><b>Spoiler</b> for <i>possible spoilers</i>: <input type="button" value="Show" style="width:45px;font-size:10px;margin:0px;padding:0px;" onClick="if (this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display != 'inline') { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'inline'; this.value = 'Hide'; } else { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'none';  this.value = 'Show'; }">
</div>
<div class="alt2" style="margin: 0px; padding: 6px; border: 1px inset;">
<div style="display: none;">
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px"><b>Spoiler</b> for <i>I'm serious!</i>: <input type="button" value="Show" style="width:45px;font-size:10px;margin:0px;padding:0px;" onClick="if (this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display != 'inline') { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'inline'; this.value = 'Hide'; } else { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'none';  this.value = 'Show'; }">
</div>
<div class="alt2" style="margin: 0px; padding: 6px; border: 1px inset;">
<div style="display: none;">
<br />
The theory is that the Pale Tree, from which all Sylvari is born, is a dragon.<br />
 
</div>
</div>
</div><br />
 
</div>
</div>
</div><br />
<br />
Woah what? Right? Supporting evidence below!<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px"><b>Spoiler</b> for <i>speculation</i>: <input type="button" value="Show" style="width:45px;font-size:10px;margin:0px;padding:0px;" onClick="if (this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display != 'inline') { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'inline'; this.value = 'Hide'; } else { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'none';  this.value = 'Show'; }">
</div>
<div class="alt2" style="margin: 0px; padding: 6px; border: 1px inset;">
<div style="display: none;">
<br />
So first let's go over the simple background information.<br />
<br />
The Sylvari are a new race on Tyria, only recently awakened. Coincidentally during the same time when the dragons have begun to awaken. Some Sylvari even make mention of this in the starting zone. One girl wonders why else do they exist, if not to fight dragons?<br />
<br />
The lore behind the Sylvari states that a human warrior returned home to find his family murdered and his town burned to the ground. The human warrior swore off war, and began to trek around the world. On one such adventure he found a strange seed, which he eventually returned and planted at the location of his lost village.<br />
<br />
He also met an old Centaur (who the humans are warring with) who was also tired of war. They began a community that attempted to create a haven away from war, but it eventually dwindled and died as well. Before his own death, the Centaur (Ventari) created a philosophy and inscribed it's rules on tablets, and left them at the base of the tree.<br />
<br />
Eventually the Pale Tree grew, and started spawning Sylvari. It's important to note that they are generally fully functioning upon awakening. The time of their lives when they would be learning is done inside &quot;the dream&quot;. The dream itself is a stored collection of all Sylvari experiences and knowledge, though individual Sylvari are not exposed to all of it. The one thing they all (most?) are exposed to, is the wisdom from the Ventari tablets.<br />
<br />
This explains both the Sylvari's tendency towards righteousness and justice, their curious nature, and (I think) their humanoid forms. Next is the most interesting part.<br />
<br />
Every one of the playable races has an enemy force consisting of their own kind. With the Sylvari, they have &quot;the Nightmare Court&quot;. This is a group of Sylvari with negative impressions of other races, but more importantly, they believe that the Ventari tablets are evil and have corrupted their race. Their aim is to remove the Pale Tree of it's influence and return the Sylvari to their true form. They do this by saturating the dream with hatred and negative emotion (hence, the nightmare).<br />
<br />
Now anyone's first inclination is to dismiss this completely. From our own point of view, the Sylvari are good and the Nightmare Court is evil. But that's a human point of view, and Sylvari are not humans. I thought to myself that their argument actually makes a lot of sense. The tablets' teachings have created a race empathetic to civilization but they are absolutely not the most natural form they could possibly take. It's an outside influence, like if you pour radioactive waste on a pitbull and it turns into a guinea pig.<br />
<br />
I then heard of this theory and it all clicked into place. Dragons are described as forces of nature, so massive that they don't directly interact with those they are destroying. Their presence creates champions from lesser races that do the grunt work for them. The Pale Tree, or by extension &quot;the dream&quot;, could very well be a dragon representing nature itself. <br />
<br />
It's worth pointing out that the form the nightmare takes during the first few minutes of playing a Sylvari, is that of a dragon. And of course, this isn't the first time nature, dragons, and dreams have been combined into one entity. ;)<br />
<br />
 
</div>
</div>
</div><br />
<br />
Below is the video if anyone wants to watch it. I am putting it in spoiler tags as well, because the title itself is a spoiler.<br />
