		<item>
			<title>Guild Wars 2 Guild Wars 2 - Thoughts and Reviews</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?74031-Guild-Wars-2-Thoughts-and-Reviews&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Mon, 27 Aug 2012 16:10:47 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[Yeah, I know we already have a number of other GW2 posts up but I figured now's a good time to start a new one post-launch after things have settled down a bit.  My thinking is that this is for the people who are on the fence and interested in the game but intimidated by the other posts which...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Yeah, I know we already have a number of other GW2 posts up but I figured now's a good time to start a new one post-launch after things have settled down a bit.  My thinking is that this is for the people who are on the fence and interested in the game but intimidated by the other posts which aren't as focused on &quot;selling&quot; the game.  With that said, here are my thoughts.<br />
<br />
My, overly, long review of Guild Wars 2.<br />
<br />
First of all, I'd like to come right out and say that I love this game.  I'm having a blast and haven't had this much fun since the early days of Vanilla WOW.  That's not to say that there aren't issues but this game is a lot of fun.  <br />
<br />
The good - The game is simply beautiful.  They did an amazing job on optimizing things from the first open beta to launch.  It runs very smoothly and is very fluid.  <br />
<br />
The combat is amazing and definitely more skill based than WOW.  In WOW, your primary concern is to hit arbitrary caps of stats (+hit for example) and then you stand in front of an enemy and begin a rotation.  Things like Deadly Boss Mods tell you exactly how long you can stand in your spot working through your rotation before it's time to move.  As such it feels like you're playing the UI and not the game.  With Guild Wars 2, things are very fluid.  You are constantly moving and being forced to react to enemy abilities and movement.  It's not quite as good as TERA but it definitely feels like an evolution from WOW.  I know a lot of hardcore WOW players think that the game is &quot;clunky&quot; and &quot;un-responsive.&quot;  Compared to WOW it might seem that way because of how different the games go about combat.  In WOW, you hit a button and numbers appear.  In Guild Wars 2, things are animation based so you hit a button and your character swings his sword.  Once that sword connects with his enemy, numbers appear.  But that delay from hitting the button to seeing the numbers is a bit jarring to some long-time WOW players.<br />
<br />
There is a ton to do and see.  Because of this, leveling and experience gain are very natural.  You go to a new area, here, have some experience.  Check out a Vista?  More experience.  Discovered a new item while crafting?  Experience!  I spent hours going through all the nooks and crannies of Divinty's Reach and Queensdale to find all the points of interest, waypoints, vistas and so on.  And because this is a brand new game, everything is still fresh.  That will, obviously, change.<br />
<br />
Everyone is rewarded for everything.  You see someone attacking a bear?  Feel free to jump in and help out.  They will get the experience and loot from killing the bear and so will you.  It's also amazing when the big zone boss spawns and you have 30 people working to take it down together.  Yesterday morning the Shadow Behemoth spawned in Queensdale (Human starting area) and a ton of people went and killed it.  Once it died, a chest dropped and everyone who participated in the fight could open it up and get loot.  No kill stealing, no ninja looting and no resource node ganking.  If a mining vein is up and I mine it, the vein will empty out for me but the person who got there 6 seconds later will be able to mine it as well.<br />
<br />
Quests and events are VERY fluid.  It's easy to get caught up in things and lose track of time.  I can't count how many times I was thinking that I need to head back to Divinity's Reach (the human capitol city) and then get caught up in a Dynamic Event.  Two hours later I've completely forgotten that I was planning to head back to the city because one event led to another and pulled me WAY off course.  That's good stuff and I love it.<br />
<br />
The Bad - Launch day issues were pretty brutal.  The servers were slammed and people were unable to play for hours on Saturday.  The Trading Post (the auction house analogue) is, still, not working.  Mail is hit or miss right now.  These things are all normal with the launch of a big title but they are still annoying.  All of this will get fixed (if it hasn't been fixed already) but it still leaves a sour taste in people's mouths.<br />
<br />
Lack of content.  I know that this sounds weird because there is a TON of stuff to do, but, there are some severe leveling gaps.  You can't simply go out and do all the &quot;Heart&quot; quests (which are the closest thing you have to standard WOW's quests) and move on to the next area.  You need to keep up on crafting, exploration, dynamic events and your personal story and there are times where you are still going to be too low for the next area with everything lower level completed.  While some people might suggest going to a different race's area, I don't buy that argument.  I want to do Human stuff and I don't care about the Charr's problems right now.  When I create a Charr, then I'll worry about it.<br />
<br />
Indifferent - The big thing is that this isn't WOW.  That's going to be a major plus for some people and a major turn off for others.  Combat plays completely differently and questing doesn't hold your hand in the same way.<br />
<br />
Cash Shop.  This is going to make ArenaNet a TON of money.  I've already dropped $20.00 on it and I'm thinking of dropping another $20.00 for bank and bag upgrades.  Some people are going to be turned off by the very fact that you need to buy certain things (bank slots, character slots) from the cash shop.  On the other hand, if you don't need it NOW, you can always wait and as you farm up gold you will be able to convert that gold into gems (the real life money currency) and buy those same slots with gold instead of real money.<br />
<br />
Personally I'm burnt out on WOW.  It's not a bad game but I've done everything and seen everything.  The quest system and combat are very stale and boring.  The lore has gotten worse and the Pandaria storyline doesn't interest me at all.  There are enough big bad guys out there (Burning Legion, Sargares, Old gods, etc.) that Pandaria just seems out of place and weak by comparison.<br />
<br />
Overall I'd give this game an A- which is the same grade I'd give WOW.  Star Wars would have been somewhere in the B- range as a comparison.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
